summary: This study investigates the effects of two different resistance training models on arterial stiffness in young, healthy women. A total of 24 untrained college women aged 18-22 were randomly assigned to one of three groups: a control group or two resistance training groups (high-intensity and high-volume). Over the course of 11 weeks, participants in the resistance training groups engaged in strength training exercises 3-5 days per week. Results showed that the control group experienced a significant increase in arterial stiffness, while both resistance training groups demonstrated significant improvements in strength across various exercises, suggesting that resistance training can enhance strength without negatively impacting vascular compliance in healthy women.
